<body>

<!-- Rain effect -->
<div class="rain-bg" id="rainBg"></div>

<div class="container">

  <header>
    <div class="badge">LeetCode #42 · Hard</div>
    <h1>Trapping Rain Water</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A visual, step-by-step guide to one of coding's most beautiful problems — explained so anyone can understand it.</p>
  </header>

  <!-- Section 1: What is the problem? -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">🤔 What's the Problem?</div>
    <p class="section-desc">Imagine you're looking at a city skyline from the side. After it rains, water collects in the "valleys" between tall buildings. How much total water is trapped?</p>

    <div class="analogy-grid">
      <div class="analogy-card">
        <div class="analogy-icon">🏙️</div>
        <h3>Think of Buildings</h3>
        <p>Each number in the array is like a building's height. A short building between two tall ones will collect water — just like a bowl!</p>
      </div>
      <div class="analogy-card">
        <div class="analogy-icon">🛁</div>
        <h3>Think of a Bathtub</h3>
        <p>Water fills to the level of the shorter wall. If one wall is height 3 and the other is height 5, water fills up to height 3 on that side.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="analogy-card">
        <div class="analogy-icon">⛰️</div>
        <h3>The Real Question</h3>
        <p>For each position, how high can water sit above it? Water height = the shorter of the two tallest walls on each side, minus the ground height.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="analogy-card">
        <div class="analogy-icon">📦</div>
        <h3>The Input & Output</h3>
        <p>Input: an array like <code style="color:var(--water)">[0,1,0,2,1,0,1,3,2,1,2,1]</code><br>Output: total water units trapped → <code style="color:var(--accent)">6</code></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 2: Interactive Visualization -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">🎮 See It Happen Live</div>
    <p class="section-desc">Watch the algorithm scan through each bar, find the tallest walls on each side, and calculate exactly how much water each position holds.</p>

    <div class="viz-container">
      <div id="bar-chart"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="legend">
      <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-box" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#64748b,#334155)"></div> Ground / Rock</div>
      <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-box" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom,rgba(56,189,248,0.7),rgba(3,105,161,0.8))"></div> Trapped Water</div>
      <div class="legend-item"><div class="legend-box" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--wall),#7c3aed)"></div> Current Position</div>
    </div>

    <div class="progress-bar"><div class="progress-fill" id="progressFill"></div></div>

    <div class="step-info" id="stepInfo">
      👆 Press <strong>Step Forward</strong> to watch the algorithm process each bar one by one, or hit <strong>Auto Play</strong> to watch it solve itself!
    </div>

    <div class="controls">
      <button class="btn-primary" onclick="stepForward()">▶ Step Forward</button>
      <button class="btn-accent" onclick="autoPlay()" id="autoBtn">⚡ Auto Play</button>
      <button class="btn-secondary" onclick="resetViz()">↺ Reset</button>
      <button class="btn-secondary" onclick="showAllWater()">💧 Show All Water</button>
    </div>

    <div class="stats-row">
      <div class="stat-card">
        <div class="stat-val" id="statCurrent" style="color:var(--wall)">—</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Current Index</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <div class="stat-val" id="statWater" style="color:var(--water)">0</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Water Collected</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-card">
        <div class="stat-val" id="statTotal" style="color:var(--accent)">6</div>
        <div class="stat-label">Total Answer</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Custom input -->
    <div style="margin-top:1.5rem; padding-top:1.5rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border);">
      <div style="font-size:0.85rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:0.4rem;">🎨 Try Your Own Array</div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <input class="array-input" id="customInput" placeholder="e.g. 4,2,0,3,2,5" value="0,1,0,2,1,0,1,3,2,1,2,1">
        <button class="btn-primary" onclick="loadCustom()">Load & Visualize</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 3: The Key Insight -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">💡 The Key Insight</div>
    <p class="section-desc">The secret to solving this problem is realizing that the water level at ANY position is determined by just two things:</p>

    <div class="step-cards">
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Find the tallest wall to the LEFT 🟢</h3>
          <p>Scan from the very beginning up to your current position. What's the tallest bar you saw? That's your left boundary — water can't go above it on the left side.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Find the tallest wall to the RIGHT 🔴</h3>
          <p>Scan from the very end back to your current position. What's the tallest bar? That's your right boundary — water can't go above it on the right side.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Take the MINIMUM of both walls 💧</h3>
          <p>Water only fills to the level of the shorter wall (it would spill over otherwise). <strong>Water level = min(left_max, right_max)</strong></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">4</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Subtract the ground height 🏔️</h3>
          <p>The ground itself takes up space. <strong>Water at position i = water_level − height[i]</strong>. If this is negative, there's no water (you're on top of a tall bar).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 4: Python Code -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">🐍 Python Solution</div>
    <p class="section-desc">Three different approaches, from simple to most efficient. Each one is explained in plain English.</p>

    <div class="tabs">
      <button class="tab active" onclick="switchTab(this,'tab1')">🧠 Easy to Understand</button>
      <button class="tab" onclick="switchTab(this,'tab2')">🚀 Efficient (Two Pointers)</button>
      <button class="tab" onclick="switchTab(this,'tab3')">📝 Step-by-Step Trace</button>
    </div>

    <div class="tab-content active" id="tab1">
      <div class="code-block"><pre><span class="cm"># ============================================
# APPROACH 1: Precompute Left & Right Maximums
# Time: O(n)  |  Space: O(n)
# ============================================</span>

<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">trap</span>(height):
    <span class="cm"># If the array is empty or too small, no water</span>
    <span class="kw">if</span> <span class="kw">not</span> height:
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="num">0</span>
    
    n = <span class="fn">len</span>(height)

    <span class="cm"># Step 1: For every position, find the tallest bar to its LEFT
    # (including itself)</span>
    left_max = [<span class="num">0</span>] * n
    left_max[<span class="num">0</span>] = height[<span class="num">0</span>]
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(<span class="num">1</span>, n):
        left_max[i] = <span class="fn">max</span>(left_max[i-<span class="num">1</span>], height[i])
    
    <span class="cm"># Step 2: For every position, find the tallest bar to its RIGHT
    # (including itself)</span>
    right_max = [<span class="num">0</span>] * n
    right_max[n-<span class="num">1</span>] = height[n-<span class="num">1</span>]
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(n-<span class="num">2</span>, -<span class="num">1</span>, -<span class="num">1</span>):
        right_max[i] = <span class="fn">max</span>(right_max[i+<span class="num">1</span>], height[i])
    
    <span class="cm"># Step 3: For each position, calculate how much water it holds</span>
    total_water = <span class="num">0</span>
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(n):
        <span class="cm"># Water level is the shorter of the two walls</span>
        water_level = <span class="fn">min</span>(left_max[i], right_max[i])
        <span class="cm"># Water above this bar = water level - bar height</span>
        water_here = water_level - height[i]
        total_water += water_here  <span class="cm"># always >= 0</span>
    
    <span class="kw">return</span> total_water

<span class="cm"># Test it!</span>
height = [<span class="num">0</span>,<span class="num">1</span>,<span class="num">0</span>,<span class="num">2</span>,<span class="num">1</span>,<span class="num">0</span>,<span class="num">1</span>,<span class="num">3</span>,<span class="num">2</span>,<span class="num">1</span>,<span class="num">2</span>,<span class="num">1</span>]
<span class="fn">print</span>(trap(height))  <span class="cm"># Output: 6 ✓</span></pre></div>
    </div>

    <div class="tab-content" id="tab2">
      <div class="code-block"><pre><span class="cm"># ============================================
# APPROACH 2: Two Pointers (Best!)
# Time: O(n)  |  Space: O(1) — no extra arrays!
# ============================================</span>

<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">trap</span>(height):
    <span class="kw">if</span> <span class="kw">not</span> height:
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="num">0</span>

    <span class="cm"># Two pointers — start from both ends and move inward</span>
    left, right = <span class="num">0</span>, <span class="fn">len</span>(height) - <span class="num">1</span>
    
    <span class="cm"># Track the highest bar seen so far from each side</span>
    left_max = right_max = <span class="num">0</span>
    
    total_water = <span class="num">0</span>

    <span class="kw">while</span> left &lt; right:
        <span class="kw">if</span> height[left] &lt; height[right]:
            <span class="cm"># The LEFT side is the limiting factor</span>
            <span class="kw">if</span> height[left] &gt;= left_max:
                left_max = height[left]   <span class="cm"># new max on left</span>
            <span class="kw">else</span>:
                total_water += left_max - height[left]  <span class="cm"># water!</span>
            left += <span class="num">1</span>
        <span class="kw">else</span>:
            <span class="cm"># The RIGHT side is the limiting factor</span>
            <span class="kw">if</span> height[right] &gt;= right_max:
                right_max = height[right]  <span class="cm"># new max on right</span>
            <span class="kw">else</span>:
                total_water += right_max - height[right]  <span class="cm"># water!</span>
            right -= <span class="num">1</span>

    <span class="kw">return</span> total_water

<span class="cm"># Why does this work?
# If left wall &lt; right wall → left is the bottleneck.
# We already know there's a right wall that's taller,
# so water is fully determined by the left max alone!
# Same logic applies when right wall &lt; left wall.</span></pre></div>
    </div>

    <div class="tab-content" id="tab3">
      <div class="code-block"><pre><span class="cm"># ============================================
# STEP-BY-STEP TRACE for [3,0,1,0,4,0,2]
# Answer should be: 10
# ============================================</span>

height  = [<span class="num">3</span>, <span class="num">0</span>, <span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">0</span>, <span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">0</span>, <span class="num">2</span>]
left_max= [<span class="num">3</span>, <span class="num">3</span>, <span class="num">3</span>, <span class="num">3</span>, <span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">4</span>]  <span class="cm"># highest bar to the left</span>
right_max=[<span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">2</span>, <span class="num">2</span>]  <span class="cm"># highest bar to the right</span>

<span class="cm"># At each index i:
#   water_level = min(left_max[i], right_max[i])
#   water_here  = water_level - height[i]

# i=0: min(3,4)=3,  3-3 = 0  (it's a wall, no water on top)
# i=1: min(3,4)=3,  3-0 = 3  💧💧💧
# i=2: min(3,4)=3,  3-1 = 2  💧💧
# i=3: min(3,4)=3,  3-0 = 3  💧💧💧
# i=4: min(4,4)=4,  4-4 = 0  (it's the tallest wall)
# i=5: min(4,2)=2,  2-0 = 2  💧💧
# i=6: min(4,2)=2,  2-2 = 0  (it's a wall)

# Total = 0+3+2+3+0+2+0 = 10 ✓</span>

<span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="str">"Total water trapped:"</span>, <span class="fn">trap</span>(height))  <span class="cm"># 10</span></pre></div>
    </div>
